{"title_page": "Marc Anthony", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer, songwriter, actor and record producer from New York}}\n{{Other uses|Mark Anthony (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Marc Anthony\n| image              = Marc Anthony 2010.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Anthony in 2010\n| birth_name         = Marco Antonio Mu\u00f1iz\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1968|9|16}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|Songwriter|Actor|Record executive|Television producer|Philanthropist}}\n| years_active       = 1988\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{ubl|{{marriage|Maria Von Ritchie Lopez<br>|1998|2000|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|[[Dayanara Torres]]<br>|2000|2004|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|[[Jennifer Lopez]]<br>|2004|2014|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|Shannon de Lima<br>|2014|2017|end=divorced}}}}\n| children           = 6\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = {{hlist|[[Latin music (genre)|Latin]]|[[Salsa music|Salsa]]|[[Tropical music|Tropical]]|[[Freestyle music|Freestyle]]|[[Adult Contemporary music|Adult contemporary]]|[[R&B music|R&B]]|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[Soft rock]]}}\n| label              = {{hlist|[[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony]]|[[Blue Dog Records|Blue Dog]]|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]|[[RMM Records & Video|RMM]]|[[Colombia Records|Colombia]]}}\n| associated_acts    = {{hlist|[[Jennifer Lopez]]|[[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]]|[[Gente De Zona]]|[[Will Smith]]|[[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]]}}\n| website            = {{URL|www.marcanthonyonline.com}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Marco Antonio Mu\u00f1iz''' (born September 16, 1968),<ref name=biographydotcom>{{cite web| url = http://www.biography.com/people/marc-anthony-241193 | title= Marc Anthony Biography: Singer (1968\u2013)| publisher= [[Biography.com]] ([[FYI (TV network)|FYI]] / [[A&E Networks]]) |accessdate=February 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"filmref\">{{cite web| url = http://www.filmreference.com/film/12/Marc-Anthony.html | title=Marc Anthony Biography (1968-)| publisher=FilmReference.com |accessdate=February 4, 2015}}</ref> known professionally as '''Marc Anthony''', is an American singer , songwriter, actor, record executive, television producer and philanthropist. Anthony is also the top selling tropical [[salsa music|salsa]] artist of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorkcitytheatre.com/theaters/barclays-center/marc-anthony.php |title=Barclays Center New York, NY - Marc Anthony - tickets, information, reviews |publisher=Newyorkcitytheatre.com |date=February 16, 2013 |accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref> The two-time [[Grammy Award]] and six-time [[Latin Grammy Award]] winner has sold more than 12&nbsp;million albums worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hunt|first1=Christopher|title=The Best Advice Marc Anthony Ever Got|url=http://www.mensfitness.com/life/entertainment/best-advice-marc-anthony-ever-got|website=Men's Health.com|accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref> Known for his Latin salsa numbers and ballads, Anthony has won numerous awards and his achievements have been honored through various recognitions. He was the recipient of the 2009 [[Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute]] (CHCI) Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chci.org/about-us/our-highest-honors/|title=Our Highest Honors {{!}} Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute|date=November 27, 2017|language=en-US|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> He also received the \"2009 CHCI Chair's Lifetime Achievement Award\" on September 16, 2009.<ref>[http://www.chci.org/news/pub/music-icon-marc-anthony-to-receive-2009-chci-chairs-lifetime-achievement-award Music Icon Marc Anthony to Receive 2009 CHCI Chair's Lifetime Achievement Award \u2013 Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018084807/http://www.chci.org/news/pub/music-icon-marc-anthony-to-receive-2009-chci-chairs-lifetime-achievement-award |date=October 18, 2015 }}. Chci.org (September 16, 2009). Retrieved October 1, 2011.</ref> He holds the [[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Record]] for best-selling tropical/salsa artist and the most number-one albums on the ''Billboard'' [[Tropical Albums]] year-end charts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Latimer|first1=Brian|title=Marc Anthony Just Beat a Guinness World Record|url= https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/marc-anthony-just-beat-guinness-world-record-n513961|accessdate=February 9, 2016|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMarco Antonio Mu\u00f1iz, known by his stage name Marc Anthony, was born in [[New York City]] to parents from [[Puerto Rico]]. His mother Guillermina was a housewife. His father, Felipe Mu\u00f1iz, was a hospital cafeteria worker and musician.<ref>{{cite book|title=Pitbull - Mr. Worldwide |last=Duthel |first=Chalee |date=2012 | page=218}}</ref><ref name=\"FNCP\">{{Cite web|url=https://prpop.org/2017/01/al-bolero-el-papa-de-marc-anthony/|title=Al bolero el Pap\u00e1 de Marc Anthony]|publisher=[[National Foundation for Popular Culture]]|location=San Juan, Puerto Rico|language=es}}</ref>\n\nAnthony's parents named him after Mexican singer [[Marco Antonio Mu\u00f1iz]]. Anthony grew up in East Harlem, also known as [[Spanish Harlem]] or El Barrio, and is the youngest of eight children. He was raised [[Roman Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|last=George Rush, Joanna Molloy |first=Celeste Katz |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2004/06/06/2004-06-06_j_lo_weds_hubby__3___marries.html |title=J.Lo weds hubby No. 3 Marries Marc Anthony at her swank L.A. digs |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |quote=Both are of Puerto Rican descent and share the Catholic faith. |date=June 6, 2004 |accessdate=September 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013060522/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2004/06/06/2004-06-06_j_lo_weds_hubby__3___marries.html |archivedate=October 13, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nHis musical education began at home, where he learned to sing in both Spanish and English under the guidance of his father, Felipe, himself a professional guitarist.<ref name=\"Oboler. 2005\">{{Cite book|title=The Oxford encyclopedia of Latinos & Latinas in the United States|last=Oboler.|first=Suzanne|date=2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|others=Gonz\u00e1lez, Deena J.|isbn=019518842X|location=Oxford, UK|oclc= \t62270754}}</ref> As a child, Anthony listened to a variety of musical genres and performers, including [[Rock music|rock]], [[rhythm and blues]], [[Pop music|pop]] stars [[Jos\u00e9 Feliciano]] (Puerto Rico), [[Air Supply]] (Australia), as well as [[salsa music|salsa]] legends [[H\u00e9ctor Lavoe]] (Puerto Rico), [[Willie Col\u00f3n]] (Puerto Rico), and [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]] (Panama), among others.<ref name=\"Oboler. 2005\"/> According to Anthony, renowned Puerto Rican percussionist and bandleader [[Tito Puente]] in particular wielded a profound personal and professional influence throughout his life.<ref name=\"Oboler. 2005\"/>\n\n==Singing career==\nMu\u00f1iz began his career as a session vocalist for [[freestyle music]] and underground New York [[house music]] acts. After changing his name to avoid confusion with his namesake,<ref name=\"Oboler. 2005\"/> Anthony worked as a songwriter and backing vocalist for pop acts [[Menudo (band)|Menudo]] and the [[Latin Rascals]]. By the early 1990s, Anthony had sold more salsa records than any other performer on the planet, solidifying his position among the most important new salsa artists to emerge in the 1990s.<ref name=\"Oboler. 2005\"/> Unlike the more socially conscious New York salsa musicians of the 1960s and 1970s, or the highly produced \"romantic\" salsa artists of the 1980s, Anthony gained fame performing a salsa style that borrowed more heavily from the African American and urban genres that he listened to growing up, such as rhythm and blues and house.<ref name=\"Oboler. 2005\"/>\n\nHis first album was a freestyle music record, \"Rebel,\" which debuted in 1988 on Bluedog Records.<ref>\"Marc Anthony Biography.\" Bio.com. A&E Networks Television, n.d. Web. October 6, 2014. <http://www.biography.com/people/marc-anthony-241193>.</ref> That same year he wrote and produced \"Boy I've Been Told\" for fellow freestyle artist [[Sa-Fire]]. Then in 1989, he sang backup vocals for Ann-Marie on the freestyle club hit, \"With or Without You\" produced by [[Little Louie Vega]] and [[Todd Terry]]. A year later in 1990, with Little Louie Vega and Todd Terry, Marc wrote a duet with Chrissy I-eece, called \"You Should Know By Now.\" In 1992, still working with [[Todd Terry]], he provided vocals for \"Love Change,\" which is on the flip-side of a 12\" vinyl released by Elan and The Powermachine titled \"Here's Your Hat,\" production of Todd Terry. At the same time, he collaborated with music producer [[Little Louie Vega]], who featured the singer on many freestyle-flavored club hits \"[[Ride On The Rhythm]]\" and the \"When The Night Is Over\" album, which featured the freestyle classic \"Time.\" In 1992, Vega and Anthony opened for Latin bandleader [[Tito Puente]] at New York's [[Madison Square Garden]]. After 1992, he changed his style from freestyle to salsa and other Latin styles.\n\n===RMM records===\nAnthony was initially reluctant to become a salsa musician and declined an offer to make a salsa album when [[Ralph Mercado]], president of [[RMM Records & Video|RMM Records]], asked him. Anthony was in a taxi when he heard [[Juan Gabriel]]'s hit song, \"[[Hasta Que Te Conoc\u00ed]],\" which influenced him to change his mind and ask Mercado if he could record it as a salsa tune.<ref>[https://articles.latimes.com/1996-05-01/entertainment/ca-64824_1_marc-anthony \"Marc Anthony's Putting a Real Kick In His Salsa\"], [[Los Angeles Times]], May 1, 1996.</ref> Inspired by the music of [[Tito Puente]], [[H\u00e9ctor Lavoe]], [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]], and [[Juan Gabriel]], Anthony released his Spanish-language debut, [[Otra Nota]], in 1993. Anthony performed at the [[Radio y Musica Convention]] hosted by [[Alfredo Alonso]].<ref>[http://www.sing365.com/music/lyric.nsf/Marc-Anthony-Biography/AC2D2D4FD50CF51B4825689000141599 Marc Anthony Biography] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222208/http://www.sing365.com/music/lyric.nsf/Marc-Anthony-Biography/AC2D2D4FD50CF51B4825689000141599 |date=March 3, 2016 }}. Sing365.com. Retrieved October 1, 2011.</ref> The album also included a cover of [[Bread (band)|Bread]]'s song, \"[[Make It with You]].\" Subsequent tours throughout the Americas, including an opening slot for Blades, established Anthony as one of the new stars in salsa. In 1994, he was featured in [[La India]]'s album ''Dicen Que Soy'', on the song \"Vivir Lo Nuestro\".\n\nHis 1995 follow-up, ''Todo a su tiempo'', won Anthony a ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' award for Hot Tropical Artist of the Year. The album was also nominated for a [[Grammy]] with songs like \"Te Conozco Bien,\" \"Hasta Ayer,\" \"Nadie Como Ella,\" \"Se Me Sigue Olvidando,\" \"Te Amare,\" and \"Llegaste A Mi.\" The album has sold more than 800,000 copies and has become established as a [[Music recording sales certification|gold record]] in the United States and in Puerto Rico.\n\nAnthony's next Spanish language album, ''Contra La Coriente'', was followed by the television special ''Marc Anthony: The Concert from [[Madison Square Garden]].'' It was broadcast on [[HBO]] on [[Valentine's Day]] in 2000. The special was nominated for the Music Special of the Year by ''[[TV Guide]]''. The album's song \"[[Y Hubo Alguien]]\" became Anthony's first number-one single on the [[Billboard Hot Latin Tracks|''Billboard'' Hot Latin Tracks]] and the first by a salsa musician.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lannert|first=John|url=|title=RMM's Anthony Builds Base for Int'l Career|date=December 20, 1997|work=Billboard|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The album became the first salsa album to enter the English language [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}} After an ongoing battle with RMM, he severed ties with Ralph Mercado and left the label in 1999.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n''Otra Nota'', ''Todo a Su Tiempo'', and ''Contra La Corriente'' established him as the top-selling singer in the history of the genre, able to sell out Madison Square Garden and prestigious venues internationally.\n\n===Sony Records===\n[[File:Marc Anthony Juntos1.jpg|thumb|250px|left|Marc Anthony in 2006]]\n\nAnthony subsequently recorded the duet \"[[No Me Ames]]\" with [[Jennifer Lopez]] on her album ''[[On the 6]]'', giving her an assist in her Spanish language crossover attempt. He also recorded a duet \"[[I Want to Spend My Lifetime Loving You]]\" with [[Tina Arena]], written by [[James Horner]] for the latter's soundtrack for the 1998 [[swashbuckling]] movie ''[[The Mask of Zorro]]''.\n\nIn 1999, riding the crossover wave of [[Ricky Martin]] and [[Enrique Iglesias]] in the Anglophone market, Anthony, working with producers [[Walter Afanasieff]], [[Cory Rooney]], [[Dan Shea (Record Producer)|Dan Shea]], and [[Rodney Jerkins]], released an English-language, [[Marc Anthony (album)|self-titled]] album with the US Top 5 single \"[[I Need to Know (Marc Anthony song)|I Need to Know]]\", and the Spanish version, \"D\u00edmelo\". His song \"[[You Sang to Me|You Sang To Me]]\" was featured in ''[[Runaway Bride (1999 film)|Runaway Bride]]''. A dance version was remixed by Dutch producer Rene Van Verseveld. The album debuted at number eight on the ''Billboard'' album chart, and six weeks later went platinum; it eventually was certified triple platinum.The song \"I Need To Know\" earned a Grammy nomination for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance.\n\n{{listen\n|title = \"Tu Amor Me Hace Bien\" (2005)\n|filename = Marc Anthony - Tu Amor Me Hace Bien.ogg\n|description = Sample of the song \"Tu Amor Me Hace Bien\" from the album ''Vali\u00f3 la Pena''. The song was produced by longtime collaborator Sergio George, who worked on most of Anthony's salsa albums.\n}}\n\nIn 2001, he debuted another salsa album, ''Libre'', which was certified gold with songs like \"Celos\", \"Este Loco Que Te Mira\", and \"Viviendo\". The album spent 14 weeks at the number-one spot on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] chart. The year after that, he made another English-language album, ''Mended''.\n\nIn June 2004, Anthony released a Latin pop album, ''[[Amar Sin Mentiras]]''. The following month, he reintroduced its songs with a danceable salsa rhythm in another album, ''Valio La Pena''. The song \"Escap\u00e9monos\" was a duet with [[Jennifer Lopez]]. In the 2005 [[Latin Grammy Awards]], his ''Amar Sin Mentiras'' won best Latin Pop Album of The Year, and his ''Vali\u00f3 La Pena'' won Best Tropical Album of the Year. Lopez and Anthony performed \"Escap\u00e9monos\" at the [[Grammy Awards of 2005|2005 Grammy Awards]].\n\nOn July 11, 2006, Anthony released ''Sigo Siendo Yo'', a Spanish greatest-hits album. In May 2010 he released ''[[Iconos]]'', a tribute to old Latin songs by artists such as [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Perales]], [[Juan Gabriel]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Jos\u00e9]].<ref>[http://www.sonicomusica.info/2010/03/marc-anthony-iconos-nuevo-disco-2010/ Marc Anthony Iconos Nuevo Disco 2010 \u2013 Blog SonicoMusica.com para escuchar buena musica online]. Sonicomusica.info (February 22, 1999). Retrieved October 1, 2011.</ref> In 2012, he released a new song called \"Cautivo De Este Amor.\" In the same year, Anthony was inducted into the [[Billboard Latin Music Hall of Fame|''Billboard'' Latin Music Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web| date = April 26, 2012| title = Billboard Latin Music Awards: Don Omar, Prince Royce Win Big|last=Cobo |first= Leila| work = Billboard| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.| url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/489976/billboard-latin-music-awards-don-omar-prince-royce-win-big| accessdate = April 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, it was announced that Anthony was recording a salsa album alongside longtime producer [[Sergio George]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/473897/marc-anthony-recording-salsa-album-for-2013|title=Marc Anthony Recording Salsa Album for 2013|last=Cantor-Navas|first=Judy|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=December 3, 2012|accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref> ''Vivir Mi Vida'', a Spanish adaptation of [[Khaled (musician)|Khaled]]'s song \"[[C'est la vie (Khaled song)|C'est la vie]]\", was released as the lead single on April 25, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/entertainment/music/marc-anthony-to-launch-first-single-73651.html|title=Marc Anthony to Launch First Single|work=[[Indiatimes]]|publisher=[[The Times of India Group]]}}</ref> In July 2013, Anthony released [[3.0 (Marc Anthony album)|3.0]], a salsa album including his song \"[[Vivir Mi Vida]]\". Since the release, the album has been certified Platinum. In addition to the new album, Anthony announced his [[Vivir Mi Vida World Tour]] and traveled across 15 countries on three continents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin-notas/1567119/marc-anthony-announces-tour-of-latin-america-us-and-australia|title=Marc Anthony Announces Tour of Latin America, US and Australia|publisher=}}</ref> After the tour, Anthony announced a second world tour for his album [[3.0 (Marc Anthony album)|3.0]], his Cambio de Piel Tour.\n\nAfter his Cambio de Piel Tour, Marc Anthony kicked off UNIDO2,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6517043/marc-anthony-carlos-vives-joint-tour|title=Marc Anthony & Carlos Vives Announce Joint Tour|publisher=}}</ref> his international tour with Carlos Vives. Marc Anthony is in constant demand for touring. After The Vivir Mi Vida world tour, one of PollStar's top selling tours of 2013, was extended to May 2014 by popular demand, and received a Premio Juventud for Super Tour of the Year. Gigant3S, his US and Latin American tour with Marco Antonio Solis and Chayanne, topped 2012's Billboard Hot Latin Tours charts.\n\nAnthony sang \"God Bless America\" at the [[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game]] at [[Citi Field]].\n\nIn September 2016, part of his tour \"Marc Anthony Live\" included 5 dates at Radio City Music Hall. Of the five shows, three were sold out.\n\n==Acting career==\nAnthony played supporting roles in projects including 1995's ''[[Hackers (film)|Hackers]]'', and 1996's ''[[Big Night]]'' and ''[[The Substitute]]''. He appeared with [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]] and Puerto Rican pop singer [[Ednita Nazario]] in [[Paul Simon]]'s 1998 stage musical, ''[[The Capeman]]'', which ran for 68 performances. He had a role in [[Martin Scorsese]]'s 1999 drama ''[[Bringing Out the Dead]]'', and in 2001, opposite [[Salma Hayek]], was in the film ''[[In the Time of the Butterflies (film)|In the Time of the Butterflies]]''. In ''[[Man on Fire (2004 film)|Man On Fire]]'' (2004), Anthony, opposite [[Denzel Washington]], played a wealthy businessman who hires a former U.S. Special Forces Soldier to protect his daughter from kidnappers in [[Mexico City]]. In 2007, Anthony starred in ''[[El Cantante]]'', a biographical drama about the life of salsa music legend [[H\u00e9ctor Lavoe]], who died in 1993 from AIDS complications. Anthony's then-wife, [[Jennifer Lopez]], narrated the story and portrayed Lavoe's wife. The film, released in August 2007, received strong reviews. In 2010, Anthony guest-starred in two episodes of the TNT medical drama ''[[Hawthorne (TV series)|HawthoRNe]]'' as a detective and the title character's ([[Jada Pinkett Smith]]) love interest. He was later named the executive music producer of the show.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/marc-anthony-named-executive-music-195144 | title=Marc Anthony Named Executive Music Producer of 'Hawthorne' | author=Justino Aguila | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=June 6, 2011 | accessdate=April 2, 2016}}</ref> Anthony worked with ex-wife Lopez and director-choreographer [[Jamie King]] in late 2011 on a Latin talent series created by [[Simon Fuller]], called ''[[Q'Viva! The Chosen]]''. It follows Lopez and Anthony as they travel across 21 countries to find new talent.<ref name=\"People\">{{cite web | url= https://people.com/tv/qviva-premiere-jennifer-lopez-marc-anthony/| title=Marc Anthony & Jennifer Lopez Come Together for ''\u00a1Q'Viva! The Chosen'' | first=Aaron|last=Parsley | publisher=[[Time Inc.]] | date=January 29, 2012 | accessdate=March 21, 2012}}</ref> In 2012, Anthony guest-mentored on Season 2 of ''[[The X Factor (American TV series)|The X Factor]]''.\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n{{see also|List of awards and nominations received by Marc Anthony}}\n\nMarc Anthony has sold over 12&nbsp;million albums worldwide, receiving numerous gold and platinum certifications from the [[Recording Industry Association of America|Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA)]] along the way. He has been recognized by New York magazine as one of the Ten Most Influential New Yorkers,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marcanthonyonline.com/bio/|title=Marc Anthony - Artista tropical y salsa con record en Billboard.|publisher=}}</ref> was inaugurated into the Billboard Hall of Fame in 2012, and was given a Lifetime Achievement Award by the Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute in Washington D.C. in September 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://chci.org/about/highest_honors/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130232710/http://chci.org/about/highest_honors/ |archive-date=January 30, 2016 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> He has won a total of 29 Premio Lo Nuestro Latin Music awards, the most for any male artist, and has been honored with the ASCAP Founders Award. He's received twelve Billboard Latin Music Awards, three Billboard Awards, and a special recognition from the Univisi\u00f3n television network in the last 2 years.\n\nHe received his first [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] in 1998 for Best Latin Tropical Performance for Contra La Corriente, directed, arranged and produced by [[\u00c1ngel Pe\u00f1a (musician)|\u00c1ngel \"Cucco\" Pe\u00f1a]], followed by the first-ever [[Latin Grammy Award|Latin Grammy]] Song of the Year award for ''D\u00edmelo'' (I Need to Know) in 2000. With momentum from that hit single, Marc Anthony, his eponymous English-language album debut, went triple-platinum in the US, and helped usher in the Latin pop explosion of 1999\u20132000. In 2005 he received double best-album Grammys: Best Latin Pop Album for ''Amar Sin Mentiras'', and Best Salsa Album for ''Vali\u00f3 la Pena''.\n\nMarc Anthony has had 25 [[Billboard charts|Billboard]] chart hits \u2013 most recently, ''Vivir Mi Vida'' and ''Flor P\u00e1lida'', which have received more than over 680&nbsp;million views and 270&nbsp;million YouTube views respectively. In May 2015 he received his second [[Vevo Certified Award|Vevo PL]] certification for 100&nbsp;million views of his video ''A Quien Quiero Mentirle''. In 2013, ''Vivir Mi Vida'', the first single from ''3.0'', spent 18 consecutive weeks at #1 on [[Billboard charts|Billboard]], making it the longest-running #1 single of all time. It received the [[Latin Grammy Award for Record of the Year]]. Anthony was honored as the [[Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year|Person of the Year]] by the [[Latin Recording Academy]] on November 16, 2016, for his musical contributions and philanthropic work.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Flores|first1=Griselda|title=Marc Anthony Honored by Colleagues During Person of the Year Ceremony: 'I Feel More Alive Than Ever'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7581161/marc-anthony-person-of-the-year-latin-recording-academy-ceremony|website=Billboard|accessdate=November 18, 2016|date=November 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\n=== Philanthropy ===\nMarc Anthony and entrepreneur Henry C\u00e1rdenas launched the Maestro Cares Foundation in January 2012.<ref>[http://www.maestrocares.org/ Maestro Cares Foundation] official website</ref> In 2014, the foundation opened an orphanage in [[La Romana, Dominican Republic|La Romana]], [[Dominican Republic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ninosdecristo.org/news/new-all-male-orphanage/|title=New All-Male Orphanage|website=www.ninosdecristo.org|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref> In 2015, the foundation opened a youth home and school in [[Barranquilla]], Colombia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elcomercio.pe/economia/peru/conoce-maba-proyecto-educativo-que-marc-anthony-apoya-noticia-1803890|title=Conoce Maba, el proyecto educativo que Marc Anthony apoya|website=El Comercio|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Anthony teamed-up with his ex-wife Jennifer Lopez and [[Alex Rodriguez]] to host ''One Voice: Somos Live!'', a telethon supporting efforts to aid Puerto Rico's recovery in the aftermath of [[Hurricane Maria]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-entertainment-news-updates-bicoastal-one-voice-somos-live-1507750572-htmlstory.html |title=Jennifer Lopez, Marc Anthony anchor star-studded 'One Voice: Somos Live!' telethon for disaster relief |last=Lewis |first=Randy |date=October 11, 2017 |website=www.latimes.com |publisher=The Los Angeles Times |access-date=October 12, 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n=== Entrepreneurship ===\nAnthony became a minority owner of the Miami Dolphins in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4344721|title=Singer Marc Anthony buys stake in Dolphins|website=ESPN.com|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref> In 2011, he returned to television on the [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]] series ''[[Hawthorne (TV series)|Hawthorne]]'', toured the U.S., and launched his line of clothes and luxury accessories for Kohl's.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/467567/marc-anthony-launches-kohls-clothing-line-kicks-off-tour-friday|title=Marc Anthony Officially Launches Kohl's Clothing Line, Kicks off Tour Friday|website=Billboard|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref> Together with Jamie King and Jennifer Lopez, he produced the 2012 TV series ''[[\u00a1Q'Viva! The Chosen|\u00a1Q' Viva! The Chosen]]'', which aired simultaneously on Spanish and English television in the US and Latin America. In April 2015, Anthony announced the formation of the entertainment company Magnus Media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6835233/marc-anthony-magnus-media-latin-music-athletes|title=Marc Anthony Wants to Empower Latin Music Artists (and Athletes) With His Magnus Media: It 'Was Born Out of Frustration'|website=Billboard|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6545800/marc-anthony-magnus-media-launch-own-company|title=Marc Anthony Goes Mogul, Launches His Own Entertainment Company Magnus Media|website=Billboard|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Marc Anthony, Jennifer Lopez.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Jennifer Lopez]] and Marc Anthony, with [[Nancy Pelosi]] and [[Nydia Vel\u00e1zquez]]]]\nAnthony is a supporter of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], and performed \"The Star-Spangled Banner\" at the [[2012 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/click/2012/09/marc-anthony-sings-the-national-anthem-video-134745.html| work=Politico | title=Marc Anthony sings the national anthem | date=September 6, 2012 | first= | last=}}</ref> In 2016, he and his ex-wife Jennifer Lopez co-hosted a concert in support of [[Hillary Clinton]]'s [[Hillary Clinton 2016 presidential campaign|presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.com/music/jlo-marc-anthony-perform-together-miami-clinton-concert/ |title=Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony Join Up in Miami for a Hillary Clinton Concert |last=Bakkila |first=Blake |date=October 30, 2016 |website=www.people.com |access-date=August 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAnthony is a practicing [[Roman Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|title=En Exclusiva: As\u00ed fue la boda de Marc Anthony y Shannon de Lima|url=http://www.univision.com/shows/despierta-america/en-exclusiva-asi-fue-la-boda-de-marc-anthony-y-shannon-de-lima|website=[[Univision]]|accessdate=December 15, 2015|language=Spanish|date=November 12, 2014|quote=...tambi\u00e9n que aunque Marc ya estuvo casado por la religi\u00f3n cat\u00f3lica, el padre Juan Santana, bendijo la uni\u00f3n de esta pareja y que, al final del enlace, se abrieron las puertas de una jaula de la cual salieron volando mariposas doradas.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Vanesa G. Toca|title=Cienciolog\u00eda, la religi\u00f3n de los famosos|url=http://archivo.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/398873.html|accessdate=December 15, 2015|work=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=January 8, 2007|language=Spanish|quote=Actualmente se rumora que JLo tiene problemas con su esposo, Marc Anthony, debido a que ella incursion\u00f3 en esta pr\u00e1ctica, mientras que \u00e9l debido a que ella incursion\u00f3 en esta pr\u00e1ctica, mientras que \u00e9l es cat\u00f3lico de coraz\u00f3n y no comparte el cambio de religi\u00f3n.}}</ref>\n\nAnthony performed \"The Star-Spangled Banner\" at the 2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game. While Anthony is an American of Puerto Rican descent, a controversy sprang up on social media due to some viewers' mistaken impression that he is a Mexican. In an interview, Anthony responded, \"'Let\u2019s get this straight. I was born and raised in New York. You can\u2019t get more New York than me'\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/marc-anthony-addresses-all-star-game-viewers-complaints-that-hes-not-american|title=Marc Anthony Addresses All-Star Game Viewers Complaints That He's Not American|first=Kacy|last=Ray|date=December 19, 2016|website=Fox News}}</ref>\n\n===Relationships and family===\nIn 1994, Anthony had a daughter, Arianna Mu\u00f1iz, with then girlfriend Debbie Rosado.<ref name=biographychannel>{{cite web | url =  http://www.biography.com/people/marc-anthony-241193 | title=Marc Anthony Biography Singer (1968\u2013) | publisher= [[The Biography Channel]] ([[A+E Networks]]) | accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref> Also, while dating they adopted their son, Chase Mu\u00f1iz.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.latina.com/entertainment/buzz/marc-anthony-love-life-timeline \n| title=Marc Anthony's Love Life In 5 Clicks | publisher= [[Latina (magazine)|Latina]] | accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1996 to 1998, Anthony dated and became engaged to Dominican-American actress [[Claudette Lali]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.popsugar.com/latina/photo-gallery/43716191/image/43716193/Confirmed-Debbie-Rosado-Claudette-Lali \n| title=A Look at the Many Women in Marc Anthony's Life | publisher= [[PopSugar]] | accessdate=July 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAnthony married former [[Miss Universe]] [[Dayanara Torres]] on May 9, 2000, in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]]. They have two sons, Cristian Marcus Mu\u00f1iz (born February 5, 2001) who Anthony named after the Mexican singer [[Cristian Castro]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/56854/Marc+Anthony+ya+es+papa.htm | title=Marc Anthony ya es pap\u00e1 | language=Spanish | work=[[Terra Networks]] | publisher=[[Telef\u00f3nica]] | date=April 9, 2007 | accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> and Ryan Adrian Mu\u00f1iz (born August 16, 2003). There were many problems in the marriage, and the couple separated in early 2002. They later reconciled and renewed their vows in a formal ceremony on December 7, 2002, at San Juan's Cathedral in [[Puerto Rico]]. The rocky marriage came to an end in October 2003 with Dayanara filing for divorce in January 2004. To help her recover from the divorce, Dayanara traded her engagement ring for a diamond-encrusted [[Cartier SA|Cartier]] watch and wrote the book ''Married to Me: How Committing to Myself Led to Triumph After Divorce''.\n\nAnthony married [[Jennifer Lopez]] in June 2004.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://people.com/celebrity/marc-anthony-silent-about-lopez-wedding/| title=Marc Anthony Silent About Lopez Wedding | accessdate=February 29, 2020 | work=[[People (magazine)|People]] | author=Stephen M. Silverman | date=June 8, 2004| author-link=Stephen M. Silverman }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://people.com/music/jennifer-lopez-marc-anthony-split/ | title=Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony Split | date=July 15, 2011 | work =[[People (magazine)|People]] | accessdate= November 5, 2014}}</ref> Lopez gave birth to their children, twins Emme Maribel Mu\u00f1iz and Maximilian David Mu\u00f1iz, on February 22, 2008. ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' paid $6&nbsp;million for the first photos of the twins.<ref name=\"people\">{{cite web | url=https://people.com/parents/introducing-max-2/| title=Introducing Max David and Emme Maribel Mu\u00f1iz! | work=People | accessdate=March 21, 2008}}</ref><ref>[https://people.com/parents/exclusive-jennifer-lopez-marc-anthony-welcome-twins/ EXCLUSIVE: Jennifer Lopez & Marc Anthony Welcome Twins!\u2013 Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony]. People.com (February 22, 2008). Retrieved February 29, 2020.</ref> In 2009, Anthony and Lopez purchased a stake in the [[Miami Dolphins]]. They joined several personalities in buying small stakes in the club, including [[Gloria Estefan|Gloria]] and [[Emilio Estefan]], [[Venus Williams|Venus]] and [[Serena Williams]], and [[Fergie (singer)|Fergie]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://people.com/celebrity/marc-anthony-buys-stake-in-miami-dolphins/| title=Marc Anthony Buys Stake in Miami Dolphins | first=Brian|last=Orloff | work=[[People (magazine)|People]] | date=July 21, 2009 | accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> They bought two houses in [[Brookville, New York]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2011/07/19/jennifer-lopez-marc-anthony-divorce-properties-houses-brookville-new-york/ | title=Jennifer Lopez & Marc Anthony Own $5.75 Million Worth Of Property In New York: Who Will Get It? | author=Chloe Melas | publisher=[[Hollywoodlife.com|HollywoodLife.com]] | date=July 19, 2011 | accessdate=September 5, 2014| author-link=Chloe Melas }}</ref> but Anthony and Lopez announced their separation in July 2011, with Anthony filing for divorce on April 9, 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://people.com/celebrity/marc-anthony-files-for-divorce-from-jennifer-lopez/| title=Marc Anthony Files for Divorce from Jennifer Lopez | first=Dahvi|last=Shira | work=[[People (magazine)|People]] | date=April 11, 2012 | accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> Their divorce was finalized on June 16, 2014, with Lopez retaining primary physical custody of the two children.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.tmz.com/2014/06/18/jlo-jennifer-lopez-marc-anthony-divorce-paparazzi/|title=Jennifer Lopez & Marc Anthony's Divorce Has An Anti-Paparazzi Clause| date= June 18, 2014| publisher=[[TMZ.com]]| accessdate= April 13, 2016 | quote=The divorce \u2014 2 years in the making \u2014became official Monday [June 16, 2014]. | archivedate=June 19, 2014| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20140619005100/http://www.tmz.com/2014/06/18/jlo-jennifer-lopez-marc-anthony-divorce-paparazzi/ | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAnthony and model Shannon de Lima (born January 6, 1989)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://us.hola.com/actualidad/201701066652/shannon-de-lima-mensaje-cumple/|title=En medio de su divorcio con Marc Anthony, Shannon de Lima abre su coraz\u00f3n el d\u00eda de su cumplea\u00f1os|date=January 6, 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/206706_shannon_de_lima_reflects_on_her_28th_birthday_following_marc_anthony_split|title=Shannon de Lima Reflects on Her 28th Birthday Following Marc Anthony Split|publisher=}}</ref> married on November 11, 2014, in [[La Romana, Dominican Republic]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.people.com/article/marc-anthony-marries-shannon-de-lima | title=Marc Anthony Marries Shannon de Lima | author=Tara Fowler | work=[[People (magazine)|People]] | date=November 11, 2014 | accessdate=April 2, 2016}}</ref> In November 2016, Anthony and Shannon de Lima separated,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/810430/marc-anthony-and-shannon-de-lima-separate-after-two-years-of-marriage|title=Marc Anthony and Shannon De Lima Separate After Two Years of Marriage|publisher=[[E! News]]|access-date=November 19, 2016| archivedate=January 30, 2017 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170130114256/http://www.eonline.com/news/810430/marc-anthony-and-shannon-de-lima-separate-after-two-years-of-marriage |url-status=live}}</ref> and the following month announced they plan to divorce.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/singer-marc-anthony-model-shannon-de-lima-announce-divorce-n697881 |title=Singer Marc Anthony, Model Shannon de Lima Announce Divorce |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=December 19, 2016 |accessdate=December 20, 2016 |first=Brian |last=Latimer |archivedate=December 20, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6mu1bXsY5?url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/singer-marc-anthony-model-shannon-de-lima-announce-divorce-n697881 |url-status=bot: unknown }} Additional on December 20, 2016.</ref> On February 13, 2017, Anthony and Shannon de Lima finalized their divorce.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latintimes.com/marc-anthony-shannon-de-lima-split-couple-officially-divorced-right-valentines-day-412051|title=Marc Anthony, Shannon De Lima Split: Couple Officially Divorced Right Before Valentine's Day|publisher=LatinTimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=February 14, 2017| archivedate=February 15, 2017| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170215015348/http://www.latintimes.com/marc-anthony-shannon-de-lima-split-couple-officially-divorced-right-valentines-day-412051| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n[[File:Marc Anthony 2009 White House.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Anthony performing at the [[White House]] in 2009]]\n{{Main|Marc Anthony discography}}\n{{external media\n| align  = center\n| audio1 = You may listen to Marc Anthony's interpretation of Hernandez' '''\"[[Preciosa (song)|Preciosa]]\"''' [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iEdfvyS1WnU '''here''']\n| audio2 = and '''\"Lamento Borincano\"''' [https://web.archive.org/web/20101130113627/https://www.youtube.com//watch?v=3xarctVa26s '''here''']\n}}\n\n*  ''[[When the Night is Over]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Otra Nota]]''  (1993)\n*  ''[[Todo A Su Tiempo (Marc Anthony album)|Todo a Su Tiempo]]'' (1995)\n*  ''[[Contra La Corriente (Marc Anthony album)|Contra la Corriente]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Marc Anthony (album)|Marc Anthony]]'' (1999)\n*  ''[[Libre (Marc Anthony album)|Libre]]'' (2001)\n*  ''[[Mended]]'' (2002)\n*  ''[[Amar Sin Mentiras]]''  (2004)\n*  ''[[Vali\u00f3 la Pena]]'' (2004)\n*  ''[[El Cantante (soundtrack)|El Cantante]]'' (2007)\n*  ''[[Iconos]]'' (2010)\n*  ''[[3.0 (Marc Anthony album)|3.0]]'' (2013)\n*  ''[[Opus (Marc Anthony album)|Opus]]'' (2019)\n\n==Tours==\n'''Juntos en concierto (Together in Concert) series:'''\n\n* [[Juntos en concierto 2005]] with [[Chayanne]] and [[Alejandro Fern\u00e1ndez]]\n* [[Juntos en concierto 2006]] with [[Laura Pausini]] And [[Marco Antonio Sol\u00eds]]\n* [[Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony en Concierto|Juntos en concierto 2007]] with [[Jennifer Lopez]]\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n[[File:Marc Anthony..jpg|thumb|250px|Anthony in 2011]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1988\n|''East Side Story''\n| Flaco\n| Singer\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Carlito's Way]]''\n| Cameo Appearance\n| Sings \"Parece Mentira\"\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Natural Causes (1994 film)|Natural Causes]]''\n| Marine Guard\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Hackers (film)|Hackers]]''\n|Agent Kee\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Big Night]]''\n|Cristiano\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[The Substitute]]''\n| Juan Lacas\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Bringing Out The Dead]]''\n|Noel\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[In the Time of the Butterflies (film)|In the Time of the Butterflies]]''\n| Lio\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Man on Fire (2004 film)|Man on Fire]]''\n|Samuel Ramos\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[El Cantante]]''\n|[[H\u00e9ctor Lavoe]]\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[In the Heights (film)|In the Heights]]''\n|Sonny's Father\n|Filming\n|}\n\n===Television===\n* 2000: ''[[Happily Ever After: Fairy Tales for Every Child]]'' (TV series) as Mario (voice) in \"Robinita Hood\" (Season 3, Episode 12)\n* 2010\u20132011: ''[[Hawthorne (TV series)|HawthoRNe]]'' (TV series) as Officer Nick Renata in season 3, recurring in season 2\n* 2012: ''[[The X Factor (U.S.)|The X Factor]]'', as a guest judge in Season 2, Episode 9\n\n===Stage===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Play\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n|1998\n| ''[[The Capeman]]''\n| Young Salvador Agron\n| Broadway\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Biography|Music|Latin music|Film}}\n*[[List of artists who reached number one on the US Dance chart]]\n*[[List of awards and nominations received by Marc Anthony]]\n*[[List of Puerto Ricans]]\n*[[List of Number 1 Dance Hits (United States)]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Marc Anthony}}\n*[http://www.marcanthonyonline.com/ Official website]\n*[{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=marc anthony|chart=all}} Marc Anthony] at [[Billboard.com]]\n*{{IMDb name|0004711}}\n\n{{Marc Anthony}}\n{{Latin Grammy Award for Record of the Year}}\n{{Latin Grammy Award for Song of the Year}}\n{{Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anthony, Marc}}\n[[Category:Marc Anthony| ]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:American freestyle musicians]]\n[[Category:American dance musicians]]\n[[Category:American Latin pop singers]]\n[[Category:American lyricists]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American musicians of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American salsa musicians]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin music songwriters]]\n[[Category:Latin pop singers]]\n[[Category:Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year honorees]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from East Harlem]]\n[[Category:RMM Records artists]]\n[[Category:Salsa musicians]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Sony Music Latin artists]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language singers of the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Brookville, New York]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer, songwriter, actor and record producer from New York}}\n{{Other uses|Mark Anthony (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Marc Anthony\n| image              = Marc Anthony 2010.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Anthony in 2010\n| birth_name         = Marco Antonio Mu\u00f1iz\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1968|9|16}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|Songwriter|Actor|Record executive|Television producer|Philanthropist}}\n| years_active       = 1988\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{ubl|{{marriage|Maria Von Ritchie Lopez<br>|1998|2000|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|[[Dayanara Torres]]<br>|2000|2004|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|[[Jennifer Lopez]]<br>|2004|2014|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|Shannon de Lima<br>|2014|2017|end=divorced}}}}\n| children           = 6\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = {{hlist|[[Latin music (genre)|Latin]]|[[Salsa music|Salsa]]|[[Tropical music|Tropical]]|[[Freestyle music|Freestyle]]|[[Adult Contemporary music|Adult contemporary]]|[[R&B music|R&B]]|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[Soft rock]]}}\n| label              = {{hlist|[[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony]]|[[Blue Dog Records|Blue Dog]]|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]|[[RMM Records & Video|RMM]]|[[Colombia Records|Colombia]]}}\n| associated_acts    = {{hlist|[[Jennifer Lopez]]|[[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]]|[[Gente De Zona]]|[[Will Smith]]|[[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]]}}\n| website            = {{URL|www.marcanthonyonline.com}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Marco Antonio Mu\u00f1iz''' (born September 16, 1968),<ref name=biographydotcom>{{cite web| url = http://www.biography.com/people/marc-anthony-241193 | title= Marc Anthony Biography: Singer (1968\u2013)| publisher= [[Biography.com]] ([[FYI (TV network)|FYI]] / [[A&E Networks]]) |accessdate=February 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"filmref\">{{cite web| url = http://www.filmreference.com/film/12/Marc-Anthony.html | title=Marc Anthony Biography (1968-)| publisher=FilmReference.com |accessdate=February 4, 2015}}</ref> known professionally as '''Marc Anthony''', is an American-born Puerto Rican singer, songwriter, actor, record executive, television producer and philanthropist. Anthony is also the top selling tropical [[salsa music|salsa]] artist of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorkcitytheatre.com/theaters/barclays-center/marc-anthony.php |title=Barclays Center New York, NY - Marc Anthony - tickets, information, reviews |publisher=Newyorkcitytheatre.com |date=February 16, 2013 |accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref> The two-time [[Grammy Award]] and six-time [[Latin Grammy Award]] winner has sold more than 12&nbsp;million albums worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hunt|first1=Christopher|title=The Best Advice Marc Anthony Ever Got|url=http://www.mensfitness.com/life/entertainment/best-advice-marc-anthony-ever-got|website=Men's Health.com|accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref> Known for his Latin salsa numbers and ballads, Anthony has won numerous awards and his achievements have been honored through various recognitions. He was the recipient of the 2009 [[Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute]] (CHCI) Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chci.org/about-us/our-highest-honors/|title=Our Highest Honors {{!}} Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute|date=November 27, 2017|language=en-US|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> He also received the \"2009 CHCI Chair's Lifetime Achievement Award\" on September 16, 2009.<ref>[http://www.chci.org/news/pub/music-icon-marc-anthony-to-receive-2009-chci-chairs-lifetime-achievement-award Music Icon Marc Anthony to Receive 2009 CHCI Chair's Lifetime Achievement Award \u2013 Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018084807/http://www.chci.org/news/pub/music-icon-marc-anthony-to-receive-2009-chci-chairs-lifetime-achievement-award |date=October 18, 2015 }}. Chci.org (September 16, 2009). Retrieved October 1, 2011.</ref> He holds the [[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Record]] for best-selling tropical/salsa artist and the most number-one albums on the ''Billboard'' [[Tropical Albums]] year-end charts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Latimer|first1=Brian|title=Marc Anthony Just Beat a Guinness World Record|url= https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/marc-anthony-just-beat-guinness-world-record-n513961|accessdate=February 9, 2016|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMarco Antonio Mu\u00f1iz, known by his stage name Marc Anthony, was born in [[New York City]] to parents from [[Puerto Rico]]. His mother Guillermina was a housewife. His father, Felipe Mu\u00f1iz, was a hospital cafeteria worker and musician.<ref>{{cite book|title=Pitbull - Mr. Worldwide |last=Duthel |first=Chalee |date=2012 | page=218}}</ref><ref name=\"FNCP\">{{Cite web|url=https://prpop.org/2017/01/al-bolero-el-papa-de-marc-anthony/|title=Al bolero el Pap\u00e1 de Marc Anthony]|publisher=[[National Foundation for Popular Culture]]|location=San Juan, Puerto Rico|language=es}}</ref>\n\nAnthony's parents named him after Mexican singer [[Marco Antonio Mu\u00f1iz]]. Anthony grew up in East Harlem, also known as [[Spanish Harlem]] or El Barrio, and is the youngest of eight children. He was raised [[Roman Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|last=George Rush, Joanna Molloy |first=Celeste Katz |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2004/06/06/2004-06-06_j_lo_weds_hubby__3___marries.html |title=J.Lo weds hubby No. 3 Marries Marc Anthony at her swank L.A. digs |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |quote=Both are of Puerto Rican descent and share the Catholic faith. |date=June 6, 2004 |accessdate=September 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013060522/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2004/06/06/2004-06-06_j_lo_weds_hubby__3___marries.html |archivedate=October 13, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nHis musical education began at home, where he learned to sing in both Spanish and English under the guidance of his father, Felipe, himself a professional guitarist.<ref name=\"Oboler. 2005\">{{Cite book|title=The Oxford encyclopedia of Latinos & Latinas in the United States|last=Oboler.|first=Suzanne|date=2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|others=Gonz\u00e1lez, Deena J.|isbn=019518842X|location=Oxford, UK|oclc= \t62270754}}</ref> As a child, Anthony listened to a variety of musical genres and performers, including [[Rock music|rock]], [[rhythm and blues]], [[Pop music|pop]] stars [[Jos\u00e9 Feliciano]] (Puerto Rico), [[Air Supply]] (Australia), as well as [[salsa music|salsa]] legends [[H\u00e9ctor Lavoe]] (Puerto Rico), [[Willie Col\u00f3n]] (Puerto Rico), and [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]] (Panama), among others.<ref name=\"Oboler. 2005\"/> According to Anthony, renowned Puerto Rican percussionist and bandleader [[Tito Puente]] in particular wielded a profound personal and professional influence throughout his life.<ref name=\"Oboler. 2005\"/>\n\n==Singing career==\nMu\u00f1iz began his career as a session vocalist for [[freestyle music]] and underground New York [[house music]] acts. After changing his name to avoid confusion with his namesake,<ref name=\"Oboler. 2005\"/> Anthony worked as a songwriter and backing vocalist for pop acts [[Menudo (band)|Menudo]] and the [[Latin Rascals]]. By the early 1990s, Anthony had sold more salsa records than any other performer on the planet, solidifying his position among the most important new salsa artists to emerge in the 1990s.<ref name=\"Oboler. 2005\"/> Unlike the more socially conscious New York salsa musicians of the 1960s and 1970s, or the highly produced \"romantic\" salsa artists of the 1980s, Anthony gained fame performing a salsa style that borrowed more heavily from the African American and urban genres that he listened to growing up, such as rhythm and blues and house.<ref name=\"Oboler. 2005\"/>\n\nHis first album was a freestyle music record, \"Rebel,\" which debuted in 1988 on Bluedog Records.<ref>\"Marc Anthony Biography.\" Bio.com. A&E Networks Television, n.d. Web. October 6, 2014. <http://www.biography.com/people/marc-anthony-241193>.</ref> That same year he wrote and produced \"Boy I've Been Told\" for fellow freestyle artist [[Sa-Fire]]. Then in 1989, he sang backup vocals for Ann-Marie on the freestyle club hit, \"With or Without You\" produced by [[Little Louie Vega]] and [[Todd Terry]]. A year later in 1990, with Little Louie Vega and Todd Terry, Marc wrote a duet with Chrissy I-eece, called \"You Should Know By Now.\" In 1992, still working with [[Todd Terry]], he provided vocals for \"Love Change,\" which is on the flip-side of a 12\" vinyl released by Elan and The Powermachine titled \"Here's Your Hat,\" production of Todd Terry. At the same time, he collaborated with music producer [[Little Louie Vega]], who featured the singer on many freestyle-flavored club hits \"[[Ride On The Rhythm]]\" and the \"When The Night Is Over\" album, which featured the freestyle classic \"Time.\" In 1992, Vega and Anthony opened for Latin bandleader [[Tito Puente]] at New York's [[Madison Square Garden]]. After 1992, he changed his style from freestyle to salsa and other Latin styles.\n\n===RMM records===\nAnthony was initially reluctant to become a salsa musician and declined an offer to make a salsa album when [[Ralph Mercado]], president of [[RMM Records & Video|RMM Records]], asked him. Anthony was in a taxi when he heard [[Juan Gabriel]]'s hit song, \"[[Hasta Que Te Conoc\u00ed]],\" which influenced him to change his mind and ask Mercado if he could record it as a salsa tune.<ref>[https://articles.latimes.com/1996-05-01/entertainment/ca-64824_1_marc-anthony \"Marc Anthony's Putting a Real Kick In His Salsa\"], [[Los Angeles Times]], May 1, 1996.</ref> Inspired by the music of [[Tito Puente]], [[H\u00e9ctor Lavoe]], [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]], and [[Juan Gabriel]], Anthony released his Spanish-language debut, [[Otra Nota]], in 1993. Anthony performed at the [[Radio y Musica Convention]] hosted by [[Alfredo Alonso]].<ref>[http://www.sing365.com/music/lyric.nsf/Marc-Anthony-Biography/AC2D2D4FD50CF51B4825689000141599 Marc Anthony Biography] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222208/http://www.sing365.com/music/lyric.nsf/Marc-Anthony-Biography/AC2D2D4FD50CF51B4825689000141599 |date=March 3, 2016 }}. Sing365.com. Retrieved October 1, 2011.</ref> The album also included a cover of [[Bread (band)|Bread]]'s song, \"[[Make It with You]].\" Subsequent tours throughout the Americas, including an opening slot for Blades, established Anthony as one of the new stars in salsa. In 1994, he was featured in [[La India]]'s album ''Dicen Que Soy'', on the song \"Vivir Lo Nuestro\".\n\nHis 1995 follow-up, ''Todo a su tiempo'', won Anthony a ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' award for Hot Tropical Artist of the Year. The album was also nominated for a [[Grammy]] with songs like \"Te Conozco Bien,\" \"Hasta Ayer,\" \"Nadie Como Ella,\" \"Se Me Sigue Olvidando,\" \"Te Amare,\" and \"Llegaste A Mi.\" The album has sold more than 800,000 copies and has become established as a [[Music recording sales certification|gold record]] in the United States and in Puerto Rico.\n\nAnthony's next Spanish language album, ''Contra La Coriente'', was followed by the television special ''Marc Anthony: The Concert from [[Madison Square Garden]].'' It was broadcast on [[HBO]] on [[Valentine's Day]] in 2000. The special was nominated for the Music Special of the Year by ''[[TV Guide]]''. The album's song \"[[Y Hubo Alguien]]\" became Anthony's first number-one single on the [[Billboard Hot Latin Tracks|''Billboard'' Hot Latin Tracks]] and the first by a salsa musician.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lannert|first=John|url=|title=RMM's Anthony Builds Base for Int'l Career|date=December 20, 1997|work=Billboard|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The album became the first salsa album to enter the English language [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}} After an ongoing battle with RMM, he severed ties with Ralph Mercado and left the label in 1999.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n''Otra Nota'', ''Todo a Su Tiempo'', and ''Contra La Corriente'' established him as the top-selling singer in the history of the genre, able to sell out Madison Square Garden and prestigious venues internationally.\n\n===Sony Records===\n[[File:Marc Anthony Juntos1.jpg|thumb|250px|left|Marc Anthony in 2006]]\n\nAnthony subsequently recorded the duet \"[[No Me Ames]]\" with [[Jennifer Lopez]] on her album ''[[On the 6]]'', giving her an assist in her Spanish language crossover attempt. He also recorded a duet \"[[I Want to Spend My Lifetime Loving You]]\" with [[Tina Arena]], written by [[James Horner]] for the latter's soundtrack for the 1998 [[swashbuckling]] movie ''[[The Mask of Zorro]]''.\n\nIn 1999, riding the crossover wave of [[Ricky Martin]] and [[Enrique Iglesias]] in the Anglophone market, Anthony, working with producers [[Walter Afanasieff]], [[Cory Rooney]], [[Dan Shea (Record Producer)|Dan Shea]], and [[Rodney Jerkins]], released an English-language, [[Marc Anthony (album)|self-titled]] album with the US Top 5 single \"[[I Need to Know (Marc Anthony song)|I Need to Know]]\", and the Spanish version, \"D\u00edmelo\". His song \"[[You Sang to Me|You Sang To Me]]\" was featured in ''[[Runaway Bride (1999 film)|Runaway Bride]]''. A dance version was remixed by Dutch producer Rene Van Verseveld. The album debuted at number eight on the ''Billboard'' album chart, and six weeks later went platinum; it eventually was certified triple platinum.The song \"I Need To Know\" earned a Grammy nomination for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance.\n\n{{listen\n|title = \"Tu Amor Me Hace Bien\" (2005)\n|filename = Marc Anthony - Tu Amor Me Hace Bien.ogg\n|description = Sample of the song \"Tu Amor Me Hace Bien\" from the album ''Vali\u00f3 la Pena''. The song was produced by longtime collaborator Sergio George, who worked on most of Anthony's salsa albums.\n}}\n\nIn 2001, he debuted another salsa album, ''Libre'', which was certified gold with songs like \"Celos\", \"Este Loco Que Te Mira\", and \"Viviendo\". The album spent 14 weeks at the number-one spot on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] chart. The year after that, he made another English-language album, ''Mended''.\n\nIn June 2004, Anthony released a Latin pop album, ''[[Amar Sin Mentiras]]''. The following month, he reintroduced its songs with a danceable salsa rhythm in another album, ''Valio La Pena''. The song \"Escap\u00e9monos\" was a duet with [[Jennifer Lopez]]. In the 2005 [[Latin Grammy Awards]], his ''Amar Sin Mentiras'' won best Latin Pop Album of The Year, and his ''Vali\u00f3 La Pena'' won Best Tropical Album of the Year. Lopez and Anthony performed \"Escap\u00e9monos\" at the [[Grammy Awards of 2005|2005 Grammy Awards]].\n\nOn July 11, 2006, Anthony released ''Sigo Siendo Yo'', a Spanish greatest-hits album. In May 2010 he released ''[[Iconos]]'', a tribute to old Latin songs by artists such as [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Perales]], [[Juan Gabriel]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Jos\u00e9]].<ref>[http://www.sonicomusica.info/2010/03/marc-anthony-iconos-nuevo-disco-2010/ Marc Anthony Iconos Nuevo Disco 2010 \u2013 Blog SonicoMusica.com para escuchar buena musica online]. Sonicomusica.info (February 22, 1999). Retrieved October 1, 2011.</ref> In 2012, he released a new song called \"Cautivo De Este Amor.\" In the same year, Anthony was inducted into the [[Billboard Latin Music Hall of Fame|''Billboard'' Latin Music Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web| date = April 26, 2012| title = Billboard Latin Music Awards: Don Omar, Prince Royce Win Big|last=Cobo |first= Leila| work = Billboard| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.| url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/489976/billboard-latin-music-awards-don-omar-prince-royce-win-big| accessdate = April 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, it was announced that Anthony was recording a salsa album alongside longtime producer [[Sergio George]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/473897/marc-anthony-recording-salsa-album-for-2013|title=Marc Anthony Recording Salsa Album for 2013|last=Cantor-Navas|first=Judy|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=December 3, 2012|accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref> ''Vivir Mi Vida'', a Spanish adaptation of [[Khaled (musician)|Khaled]]'s song \"[[C'est la vie (Khaled song)|C'est la vie]]\", was released as the lead single on April 25, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/entertainment/music/marc-anthony-to-launch-first-single-73651.html|title=Marc Anthony to Launch First Single|work=[[Indiatimes]]|publisher=[[The Times of India Group]]}}</ref> In July 2013, Anthony released [[3.0 (Marc Anthony album)|3.0]], a salsa album including his song \"[[Vivir Mi Vida]]\". Since the release, the album has been certified Platinum. In addition to the new album, Anthony announced his [[Vivir Mi Vida World Tour]] and traveled across 15 countries on three continents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin-notas/1567119/marc-anthony-announces-tour-of-latin-america-us-and-australia|title=Marc Anthony Announces Tour of Latin America, US and Australia|publisher=}}</ref> After the tour, Anthony announced a second world tour for his album [[3.0 (Marc Anthony album)|3.0]], his Cambio de Piel Tour.\n\nAfter his Cambio de Piel Tour, Marc Anthony kicked off UNIDO2,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6517043/marc-anthony-carlos-vives-joint-tour|title=Marc Anthony & Carlos Vives Announce Joint Tour|publisher=}}</ref> his international tour with Carlos Vives. Marc Anthony is in constant demand for touring. After The Vivir Mi Vida world tour, one of PollStar's top selling tours of 2013, was extended to May 2014 by popular demand, and received a Premio Juventud for Super Tour of the Year. Gigant3S, his US and Latin American tour with Marco Antonio Solis and Chayanne, topped 2012's Billboard Hot Latin Tours charts.\n\nAnthony sang \"God Bless America\" at the [[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game]] at [[Citi Field]].\n\nIn September 2016, part of his tour \"Marc Anthony Live\" included 5 dates at Radio City Music Hall. Of the five shows, three were sold out.\n\n==Acting career==\nAnthony played supporting roles in projects including 1995's ''[[Hackers (film)|Hackers]]'', and 1996's ''[[Big Night]]'' and ''[[The Substitute]]''. He appeared with [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]] and Puerto Rican pop singer [[Ednita Nazario]] in [[Paul Simon]]'s 1998 stage musical, ''[[The Capeman]]'', which ran for 68 performances. He had a role in [[Martin Scorsese]]'s 1999 drama ''[[Bringing Out the Dead]]'', and in 2001, opposite [[Salma Hayek]], was in the film ''[[In the Time of the Butterflies (film)|In the Time of the Butterflies]]''. In ''[[Man on Fire (2004 film)|Man On Fire]]'' (2004), Anthony, opposite [[Denzel Washington]], played a wealthy businessman who hires a former U.S. Special Forces Soldier to protect his daughter from kidnappers in [[Mexico City]]. In 2007, Anthony starred in ''[[El Cantante]]'', a biographical drama about the life of salsa music legend [[H\u00e9ctor Lavoe]], who died in 1993 from AIDS complications. Anthony's then-wife, [[Jennifer Lopez]], narrated the story and portrayed Lavoe's wife. The film, released in August 2007, received strong reviews. In 2010, Anthony guest-starred in two episodes of the TNT medical drama ''[[Hawthorne (TV series)|HawthoRNe]]'' as a detective and the title character's ([[Jada Pinkett Smith]]) love interest. He was later named the executive music producer of the show.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/marc-anthony-named-executive-music-195144 | title=Marc Anthony Named Executive Music Producer of 'Hawthorne' | author=Justino Aguila | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=June 6, 2011 | accessdate=April 2, 2016}}</ref> Anthony worked with ex-wife Lopez and director-choreographer [[Jamie King]] in late 2011 on a Latin talent series created by [[Simon Fuller]], called ''[[Q'Viva! The Chosen]]''. It follows Lopez and Anthony as they travel across 21 countries to find new talent.<ref name=\"People\">{{cite web | url= https://people.com/tv/qviva-premiere-jennifer-lopez-marc-anthony/| title=Marc Anthony & Jennifer Lopez Come Together for ''\u00a1Q'Viva! The Chosen'' | first=Aaron|last=Parsley | publisher=[[Time Inc.]] | date=January 29, 2012 | accessdate=March 21, 2012}}</ref> In 2012, Anthony guest-mentored on Season 2 of ''[[The X Factor (American TV series)|The X Factor]]''.\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n{{see also|List of awards and nominations received by Marc Anthony}}\n\nMarc Anthony has sold over 12&nbsp;million albums worldwide, receiving numerous gold and platinum certifications from the [[Recording Industry Association of America|Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA)]] along the way. He has been recognized by New York magazine as one of the Ten Most Influential New Yorkers,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marcanthonyonline.com/bio/|title=Marc Anthony - Artista tropical y salsa con record en Billboard.|publisher=}}</ref> was inaugurated into the Billboard Hall of Fame in 2012, and was given a Lifetime Achievement Award by the Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute in Washington D.C. in September 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://chci.org/about/highest_honors/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130232710/http://chci.org/about/highest_honors/ |archive-date=January 30, 2016 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> He has won a total of 29 Premio Lo Nuestro Latin Music awards, the most for any male artist, and has been honored with the ASCAP Founders Award. He's received twelve Billboard Latin Music Awards, three Billboard Awards, and a special recognition from the Univisi\u00f3n television network in the last 2 years.\n\nHe received his first [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] in 1998 for Best Latin Tropical Performance for Contra La Corriente, directed, arranged and produced by [[\u00c1ngel Pe\u00f1a (musician)|\u00c1ngel \"Cucco\" Pe\u00f1a]], followed by the first-ever [[Latin Grammy Award|Latin Grammy]] Song of the Year award for ''D\u00edmelo'' (I Need to Know) in 2000. With momentum from that hit single, Marc Anthony, his eponymous English-language album debut, went triple-platinum in the US, and helped usher in the Latin pop explosion of 1999\u20132000. In 2005 he received double best-album Grammys: Best Latin Pop Album for ''Amar Sin Mentiras'', and Best Salsa Album for ''Vali\u00f3 la Pena''.\n\nMarc Anthony has had 25 [[Billboard charts|Billboard]] chart hits \u2013 most recently, ''Vivir Mi Vida'' and ''Flor P\u00e1lida'', which have received more than over 680&nbsp;million views and 270&nbsp;million YouTube views respectively. In May 2015 he received his second [[Vevo Certified Award|Vevo PL]] certification for 100&nbsp;million views of his video ''A Quien Quiero Mentirle''. In 2013, ''Vivir Mi Vida'', the first single from ''3.0'', spent 18 consecutive weeks at #1 on [[Billboard charts|Billboard]], making it the longest-running #1 single of all time. It received the [[Latin Grammy Award for Record of the Year]]. Anthony was honored as the [[Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year|Person of the Year]] by the [[Latin Recording Academy]] on November 16, 2016, for his musical contributions and philanthropic work.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Flores|first1=Griselda|title=Marc Anthony Honored by Colleagues During Person of the Year Ceremony: 'I Feel More Alive Than Ever'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7581161/marc-anthony-person-of-the-year-latin-recording-academy-ceremony|website=Billboard|accessdate=November 18, 2016|date=November 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\n=== Philanthropy ===\nMarc Anthony and entrepreneur Henry C\u00e1rdenas launched the Maestro Cares Foundation in January 2012.<ref>[http://www.maestrocares.org/ Maestro Cares Foundation] official website</ref> In 2014, the foundation opened an orphanage in [[La Romana, Dominican Republic|La Romana]], [[Dominican Republic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ninosdecristo.org/news/new-all-male-orphanage/|title=New All-Male Orphanage|website=www.ninosdecristo.org|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref> In 2015, the foundation opened a youth home and school in [[Barranquilla]], Colombia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elcomercio.pe/economia/peru/conoce-maba-proyecto-educativo-que-marc-anthony-apoya-noticia-1803890|title=Conoce Maba, el proyecto educativo que Marc Anthony apoya|website=El Comercio|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Anthony teamed-up with his ex-wife Jennifer Lopez and [[Alex Rodriguez]] to host ''One Voice: Somos Live!'', a telethon supporting efforts to aid Puerto Rico's recovery in the aftermath of [[Hurricane Maria]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-entertainment-news-updates-bicoastal-one-voice-somos-live-1507750572-htmlstory.html |title=Jennifer Lopez, Marc Anthony anchor star-studded 'One Voice: Somos Live!' telethon for disaster relief |last=Lewis |first=Randy |date=October 11, 2017 |website=www.latimes.com |publisher=The Los Angeles Times |access-date=October 12, 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n=== Entrepreneurship ===\nAnthony became a minority owner of the Miami Dolphins in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4344721|title=Singer Marc Anthony buys stake in Dolphins|website=ESPN.com|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref> In 2011, he returned to television on the [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]] series ''[[Hawthorne (TV series)|Hawthorne]]'', toured the U.S., and launched his line of clothes and luxury accessories for Kohl's.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/467567/marc-anthony-launches-kohls-clothing-line-kicks-off-tour-friday|title=Marc Anthony Officially Launches Kohl's Clothing Line, Kicks off Tour Friday|website=Billboard|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref> Together with Jamie King and Jennifer Lopez, he produced the 2012 TV series ''[[\u00a1Q'Viva! The Chosen|\u00a1Q' Viva! The Chosen]]'', which aired simultaneously on Spanish and English television in the US and Latin America. In April 2015, Anthony announced the formation of the entertainment company Magnus Media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6835233/marc-anthony-magnus-media-latin-music-athletes|title=Marc Anthony Wants to Empower Latin Music Artists (and Athletes) With His Magnus Media: It 'Was Born Out of Frustration'|website=Billboard|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6545800/marc-anthony-magnus-media-launch-own-company|title=Marc Anthony Goes Mogul, Launches His Own Entertainment Company Magnus Media|website=Billboard|access-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Marc Anthony, Jennifer Lopez.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Jennifer Lopez]] and Marc Anthony, with [[Nancy Pelosi]] and [[Nydia Vel\u00e1zquez]]]]\nAnthony is a supporter of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], and performed \"The Star-Spangled Banner\" at the [[2012 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/click/2012/09/marc-anthony-sings-the-national-anthem-video-134745.html| work=Politico | title=Marc Anthony sings the national anthem | date=September 6, 2012 | first= | last=}}</ref> In 2016, he and his ex-wife Jennifer Lopez co-hosted a concert in support of [[Hillary Clinton]]'s [[Hillary Clinton 2016 presidential campaign|presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.com/music/jlo-marc-anthony-perform-together-miami-clinton-concert/ |title=Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony Join Up in Miami for a Hillary Clinton Concert |last=Bakkila |first=Blake |date=October 30, 2016 |website=www.people.com |access-date=August 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAnthony is a practicing [[Roman Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|title=En Exclusiva: As\u00ed fue la boda de Marc Anthony y Shannon de Lima|url=http://www.univision.com/shows/despierta-america/en-exclusiva-asi-fue-la-boda-de-marc-anthony-y-shannon-de-lima|website=[[Univision]]|accessdate=December 15, 2015|language=Spanish|date=November 12, 2014|quote=...tambi\u00e9n que aunque Marc ya estuvo casado por la religi\u00f3n cat\u00f3lica, el padre Juan Santana, bendijo la uni\u00f3n de esta pareja y que, al final del enlace, se abrieron las puertas de una jaula de la cual salieron volando mariposas doradas.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Vanesa G. Toca|title=Cienciolog\u00eda, la religi\u00f3n de los famosos|url=http://archivo.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/398873.html|accessdate=December 15, 2015|work=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=January 8, 2007|language=Spanish|quote=Actualmente se rumora que JLo tiene problemas con su esposo, Marc Anthony, debido a que ella incursion\u00f3 en esta pr\u00e1ctica, mientras que \u00e9l debido a que ella incursion\u00f3 en esta pr\u00e1ctica, mientras que \u00e9l es cat\u00f3lico de coraz\u00f3n y no comparte el cambio de religi\u00f3n.}}</ref>\n\nAnthony performed \"The Star-Spangled Banner\" at the 2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game. While Anthony is an American of Puerto Rican descent, a controversy sprang up on social media due to some viewers' mistaken impression that he is a Mexican. In an interview, Anthony responded, \"'Let\u2019s get this straight. I was born and raised in New York. You can\u2019t get more New York than me'\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/marc-anthony-addresses-all-star-game-viewers-complaints-that-hes-not-american|title=Marc Anthony Addresses All-Star Game Viewers Complaints That He's Not American|first=Kacy|last=Ray|date=December 19, 2016|website=Fox News}}</ref>\n\n===Relationships and family===\nIn 1994, Anthony had a daughter, Arianna Mu\u00f1iz, with then girlfriend Debbie Rosado.<ref name=biographychannel>{{cite web | url =  http://www.biography.com/people/marc-anthony-241193 | title=Marc Anthony Biography Singer (1968\u2013) | publisher= [[The Biography Channel]] ([[A+E Networks]]) | accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref> Also, while dating they adopted their son, Chase Mu\u00f1iz.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.latina.com/entertainment/buzz/marc-anthony-love-life-timeline \n| title=Marc Anthony's Love Life In 5 Clicks | publisher= [[Latina (magazine)|Latina]] | accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1996 to 1998, Anthony dated and became engaged to Dominican-American actress [[Claudette Lali]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.popsugar.com/latina/photo-gallery/43716191/image/43716193/Confirmed-Debbie-Rosado-Claudette-Lali \n| title=A Look at the Many Women in Marc Anthony's Life | publisher= [[PopSugar]] | accessdate=July 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAnthony married former [[Miss Universe]] [[Dayanara Torres]] on May 9, 2000, in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]]. They have two sons, Cristian Marcus Mu\u00f1iz (born February 5, 2001) who Anthony named after the Mexican singer [[Cristian Castro]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/56854/Marc+Anthony+ya+es+papa.htm | title=Marc Anthony ya es pap\u00e1 | language=Spanish | work=[[Terra Networks]] | publisher=[[Telef\u00f3nica]] | date=April 9, 2007 | accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> and Ryan Adrian Mu\u00f1iz (born August 16, 2003). There were many problems in the marriage, and the couple separated in early 2002. They later reconciled and renewed their vows in a formal ceremony on December 7, 2002, at San Juan's Cathedral in [[Puerto Rico]]. The rocky marriage came to an end in October 2003 with Dayanara filing for divorce in January 2004. To help her recover from the divorce, Dayanara traded her engagement ring for a diamond-encrusted [[Cartier SA|Cartier]] watch and wrote the book ''Married to Me: How Committing to Myself Led to Triumph After Divorce''.\n\nAnthony married [[Jennifer Lopez]] in June 2004.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://people.com/celebrity/marc-anthony-silent-about-lopez-wedding/| title=Marc Anthony Silent About Lopez Wedding | accessdate=February 29, 2020 | work=[[People (magazine)|People]] | author=Stephen M. Silverman | date=June 8, 2004| author-link=Stephen M. Silverman }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://people.com/music/jennifer-lopez-marc-anthony-split/ | title=Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony Split | date=July 15, 2011 | work =[[People (magazine)|People]] | accessdate= November 5, 2014}}</ref> Lopez gave birth to their children, twins Emme Maribel Mu\u00f1iz and Maximilian David Mu\u00f1iz, on February 22, 2008. ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' paid $6&nbsp;million for the first photos of the twins.<ref name=\"people\">{{cite web | url=https://people.com/parents/introducing-max-2/| title=Introducing Max David and Emme Maribel Mu\u00f1iz! | work=People | accessdate=March 21, 2008}}</ref><ref>[https://people.com/parents/exclusive-jennifer-lopez-marc-anthony-welcome-twins/ EXCLUSIVE: Jennifer Lopez & Marc Anthony Welcome Twins!\u2013 Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony]. People.com (February 22, 2008). Retrieved February 29, 2020.</ref> In 2009, Anthony and Lopez purchased a stake in the [[Miami Dolphins]]. They joined several personalities in buying small stakes in the club, including [[Gloria Estefan|Gloria]] and [[Emilio Estefan]], [[Venus Williams|Venus]] and [[Serena Williams]], and [[Fergie (singer)|Fergie]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://people.com/celebrity/marc-anthony-buys-stake-in-miami-dolphins/| title=Marc Anthony Buys Stake in Miami Dolphins | first=Brian|last=Orloff | work=[[People (magazine)|People]] | date=July 21, 2009 | accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> They bought two houses in [[Brookville, New York]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2011/07/19/jennifer-lopez-marc-anthony-divorce-properties-houses-brookville-new-york/ | title=Jennifer Lopez & Marc Anthony Own $5.75 Million Worth Of Property In New York: Who Will Get It? | author=Chloe Melas | publisher=[[Hollywoodlife.com|HollywoodLife.com]] | date=July 19, 2011 | accessdate=September 5, 2014| author-link=Chloe Melas }}</ref> but Anthony and Lopez announced their separation in July 2011, with Anthony filing for divorce on April 9, 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://people.com/celebrity/marc-anthony-files-for-divorce-from-jennifer-lopez/| title=Marc Anthony Files for Divorce from Jennifer Lopez | first=Dahvi|last=Shira | work=[[People (magazine)|People]] | date=April 11, 2012 | accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> Their divorce was finalized on June 16, 2014, with Lopez retaining primary physical custody of the two children.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.tmz.com/2014/06/18/jlo-jennifer-lopez-marc-anthony-divorce-paparazzi/|title=Jennifer Lopez & Marc Anthony's Divorce Has An Anti-Paparazzi Clause| date= June 18, 2014| publisher=[[TMZ.com]]| accessdate= April 13, 2016 | quote=The divorce \u2014 2 years in the making \u2014became official Monday [June 16, 2014]. | archivedate=June 19, 2014| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20140619005100/http://www.tmz.com/2014/06/18/jlo-jennifer-lopez-marc-anthony-divorce-paparazzi/ | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAnthony and model Shannon de Lima (born January 6, 1989)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://us.hola.com/actualidad/201701066652/shannon-de-lima-mensaje-cumple/|title=En medio de su divorcio con Marc Anthony, Shannon de Lima abre su coraz\u00f3n el d\u00eda de su cumplea\u00f1os|date=January 6, 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/206706_shannon_de_lima_reflects_on_her_28th_birthday_following_marc_anthony_split|title=Shannon de Lima Reflects on Her 28th Birthday Following Marc Anthony Split|publisher=}}</ref> married on November 11, 2014, in [[La Romana, Dominican Republic]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.people.com/article/marc-anthony-marries-shannon-de-lima | title=Marc Anthony Marries Shannon de Lima | author=Tara Fowler | work=[[People (magazine)|People]] | date=November 11, 2014 | accessdate=April 2, 2016}}</ref> In November 2016, Anthony and Shannon de Lima separated,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/810430/marc-anthony-and-shannon-de-lima-separate-after-two-years-of-marriage|title=Marc Anthony and Shannon De Lima Separate After Two Years of Marriage|publisher=[[E! News]]|access-date=November 19, 2016| archivedate=January 30, 2017 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170130114256/http://www.eonline.com/news/810430/marc-anthony-and-shannon-de-lima-separate-after-two-years-of-marriage |url-status=live}}</ref> and the following month announced they plan to divorce.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/singer-marc-anthony-model-shannon-de-lima-announce-divorce-n697881 |title=Singer Marc Anthony, Model Shannon de Lima Announce Divorce |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=December 19, 2016 |accessdate=December 20, 2016 |first=Brian |last=Latimer |archivedate=December 20, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6mu1bXsY5?url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/singer-marc-anthony-model-shannon-de-lima-announce-divorce-n697881 |url-status=bot: unknown }} Additional on December 20, 2016.</ref> On February 13, 2017, Anthony and Shannon de Lima finalized their divorce.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latintimes.com/marc-anthony-shannon-de-lima-split-couple-officially-divorced-right-valentines-day-412051|title=Marc Anthony, Shannon De Lima Split: Couple Officially Divorced Right Before Valentine's Day|publisher=LatinTimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=February 14, 2017| archivedate=February 15, 2017| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170215015348/http://www.latintimes.com/marc-anthony-shannon-de-lima-split-couple-officially-divorced-right-valentines-day-412051| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n[[File:Marc Anthony 2009 White House.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Anthony performing at the [[White House]] in 2009]]\n{{Main|Marc Anthony discography}}\n{{external media\n| align  = center\n| audio1 = You may listen to Marc Anthony's interpretation of Hernandez' '''\"[[Preciosa (song)|Preciosa]]\"''' [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iEdfvyS1WnU '''here''']\n| audio2 = and '''\"Lamento Borincano\"''' [https://web.archive.org/web/20101130113627/https://www.youtube.com//watch?v=3xarctVa26s '''here''']\n}}\n\n*  ''[[When the Night is Over]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Otra Nota]]''  (1993)\n*  ''[[Todo A Su Tiempo (Marc Anthony album)|Todo a Su Tiempo]]'' (1995)\n*  ''[[Contra La Corriente (Marc Anthony album)|Contra la Corriente]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Marc Anthony (album)|Marc Anthony]]'' (1999)\n*  ''[[Libre (Marc Anthony album)|Libre]]'' (2001)\n*  ''[[Mended]]'' (2002)\n*  ''[[Amar Sin Mentiras]]''  (2004)\n*  ''[[Vali\u00f3 la Pena]]'' (2004)\n*  ''[[El Cantante (soundtrack)|El Cantante]]'' (2007)\n*  ''[[Iconos]]'' (2010)\n*  ''[[3.0 (Marc Anthony album)|3.0]]'' (2013)\n*  ''[[Opus (Marc Anthony album)|Opus]]'' (2019)\n\n==Tours==\n'''Juntos en concierto (Together in Concert) series:'''\n\n* [[Juntos en concierto 2005]] with [[Chayanne]] and [[Alejandro Fern\u00e1ndez]]\n* [[Juntos en concierto 2006]] with [[Laura Pausini]] And [[Marco Antonio Sol\u00eds]]\n* [[Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony en Concierto|Juntos en concierto 2007]] with [[Jennifer Lopez]]\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n[[File:Marc Anthony..jpg|thumb|250px|Anthony in 2011]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1988\n|''East Side Story''\n| Flaco\n| Singer\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Carlito's Way]]''\n| Cameo Appearance\n| Sings \"Parece Mentira\"\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Natural Causes (1994 film)|Natural Causes]]''\n| Marine Guard\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Hackers (film)|Hackers]]''\n|Agent Kee\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Big Night]]''\n|Cristiano\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[The Substitute]]''\n| Juan Lacas\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Bringing Out The Dead]]''\n|Noel\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[In the Time of the Butterflies (film)|In the Time of the Butterflies]]''\n| Lio\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Man on Fire (2004 film)|Man on Fire]]''\n|Samuel Ramos\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[El Cantante]]''\n|[[H\u00e9ctor Lavoe]]\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[In the Heights (film)|In the Heights]]''\n|Sonny's Father\n|Filming\n|}\n\n===Television===\n* 2000: ''[[Happily Ever After: Fairy Tales for Every Child]]'' (TV series) as Mario (voice) in \"Robinita Hood\" (Season 3, Episode 12)\n* 2010\u20132011: ''[[Hawthorne (TV series)|HawthoRNe]]'' (TV series) as Officer Nick Renata in season 3, recurring in season 2\n* 2012: ''[[The X Factor (U.S.)|The X Factor]]'', as a guest judge in Season 2, Episode 9\n\n===Stage===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Play\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n|1998\n| ''[[The Capeman]]''\n| Young Salvador Agron\n| Broadway\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Biography|Music|Latin music|Film}}\n*[[List of artists who reached number one on the US Dance chart]]\n*[[List of awards and nominations received by Marc Anthony]]\n*[[List of Puerto Ricans]]\n*[[List of Number 1 Dance Hits (United States)]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Marc Anthony}}\n*[http://www.marcanthonyonline.com/ Official website]\n*[{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=marc anthony|chart=all}} Marc Anthony] at [[Billboard.com]]\n*{{IMDb name|0004711}}\n\n{{Marc Anthony}}\n{{Latin Grammy Award for Record of the Year}}\n{{Latin Grammy Award for Song of the Year}}\n{{Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anthony, Marc}}\n[[Category:Marc Anthony| ]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:American freestyle musicians]]\n[[Category:American dance musicians]]\n[[Category:American Latin pop singers]]\n[[Category:American lyricists]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American musicians of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American salsa musicians]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin music songwriters]]\n[[Category:Latin pop singers]]\n[[Category:Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year honorees]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from East Harlem]]\n[[Category:RMM Records artists]]\n[[Category:Salsa musicians]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Sony Music Latin artists]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language singers of the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Brookville, New York]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n", "name_user": "2600:8806:400:d6:bcc3:3ba3:bdae:97e4", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marc_Anthony"}
{"title_page": "Naoto Sawai", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Naoto Sawai <br> \u6fa4\u4e95 \u76f4\u4eba\n| image = RC Lens - AC Ajaccio (22-12-2018)104.jpg\n| image_size = 280\n| alt = \n| caption = Sawai in 2018.\n| fullname = Naoto Sawai\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1995|4|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Chiba Prefecture|Chiba]], Japan\n| height = 1.76 m\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Tokyo Verdy]]\n| clubnumber = 14\n| youthyears1 = 2004\u20132013\n| youthclubs1 = [[Tokyo Verdy]]\n| years1 = 2014\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Tokyo Verdy]]\n| caps1 = 100\n| goals1 = 8\n| years2 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[AC Ajaccio|Ajaccio II]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 13\n| goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[AC Ajaccio|Ajaccio]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 8\n| goals3 = 1\n| club-update = 1 January 2020\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Naoto Sawai'''|\u6fa4\u4e95 \u76f4\u4eba|Sawai Naoto|born 3 April 1995}} is a Japanese professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays [[Tokyo Verdy]].<ref name=\"jleague\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jleague.jp/club/tokyov/player/detail/1300209/|publisher=jleague.jp|title=\u6fa4\u4e95 \u76f4\u4eba\uff1a\u6771\u4eac\u30f4\u30a7\u30eb\u30c7\u30a3\uff1a\uff2a\u30ea\u30fc\u30b0.jp|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nSawai joined [[J2 League]] club [[Tokyo Verdy]] in 2014.\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{Updated|1 January 2020}}.<ref>Nippon Sports Kikaku Publishing inc./\u65e5\u672c\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u4f01\u753b\u51fa\u7248\u793e, [https://www.amazon.co.jp/J1-J3%E9%81%B8%E6%89%8B%E5%90%8D%E9%91%91%E3%83%8F%E3%83%B3%E3%83%87%E3%82%A3%E7%89%88-2018-NSK-MOOK/dp/4905411521 \"J1&J2&J3\u9078\u624b\u540d\u9451\u30cf\u30f3\u30c7\u30a3\u7248 2018 (NSK MOOK)\"], 7 February 2018, Japan, {{ISBN|978-4905411529}} (p. 172 out of 289)</ref><ref>Nippon Sports Kikaku Publishing inc./\u65e5\u672c\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u4f01\u753b\u51fa\u7248\u793e, [https://www.am