rk: The Macmillan Company, pp.&nbsp;208\u2013228.\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource author}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{LCAuth|n50057241|Robert Hugh Benson|63|ue}}\n===Online editions===\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=4052}}\n* {{FadedPage|id=Benson, Robert Hugh|name=Robert Hugh Benson|author=yes}}\n* {{librivox author | id=1980}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benson, Robert Hugh}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1914 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:19th-century English Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:20th-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century English Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:Advocates of colonisation]]\n[[Category:Anti-Masonry]]\n[[Category:Anti-Protestantism]]\n[[Category:Anti-abortion activists]]\n[[Category:Anti-crime activists]]\n[[Category:Anti-gambling advocates]]\n[[Category:Anti-liquor activists]]\n[[Category:Anti-pedophile activism]]\n[[Category:Anti-Russification activists]]\n[[Category:Anti-globalization activists]]\n[[Category:Anti-poverty advocates]]\n[[Category:Anti-obesity activists]]\n[[Category:Anti-suffragists]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Anglican priest converts to Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:Benson family (England)|Robert]]\n[[Category:British anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Crime victim advocates]]\n[[Category:Christian creationists]]\n[[Category:Cultural critics]]\n[[Category:Critics of Afrocentrism]]\n[[Category:Critics of Arab nationalism]]\n[[Category:Critics of animal rights]]\n[[Category:Critics of classical liberalism]]\n[[Category:Critics of multiculturalism]]\n[[Category:Critics of vegetarianism]]\n[[Category:Critics of Marxism]]\n[[Category:Critics of atheism]]\n[[Category:Critics of Judaism]]\n[[Category:Critics of Islam]]\n[[Category:Critics of Buddhism]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Elder rights activists]]\n[[Category:English anti-communists]]\n[[Category:English science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English religious writers]]\n[[Category:English children's writers]]\n[[Category:English historical novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers of historical novels set in Early Modern period]]\n[[Category:English dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English horror writers]]\n[[Category:English male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English male novelists]]\n[[Category:Farmers' rights activists]]\n[[Category:Fathers' rights activists]]\n[[Category:Ghost story writers]]\n[[Category:Gun rights advocates]]\n[[Category:Integralism]]\n[[Category:Intelligent design advocates]]\n[[Category:Male critics of feminism]]\n[[Category:People of the Victorian era]]\n[[Category:Proslavery activists]]\n[[Category:Privacy activists]]\n[[Category:Shareholder-rights activists]]\n[[Category:Social critics]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Gregory the Great]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Holy Sepulchre]]\n[[Category:Men's rights activists]]\n[[Category:Members of Anglican religious orders]]\n[[Category:Racism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Sexism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Right-wing politics in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox clergy\n| honorific_prefix   = [[The Reverend]] [[Monsignor]]\n| birth_name    = Robert Hugh Benson\n| image         = Monsignor R. H. Benson in Oct. 1912, Aged 40.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| caption       = Photo of Benson by G. Jerrard, 1912\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1871|11|18}}\n| birth_place   = [[Wellington College, Berkshire|Wellington College]], [[Berkshire]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1914|10|19|1871|11|18}}\n| death_place   = Bishop's house [[Salford Cathedral]], [[City of Salford|Salford]]\n| church        = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]\n| ordained      = 1904\n| congregations = \n| parents       = [[Edward White Benson]] and [[Mary Sidgwick Benson]]\n}}\n'''Robert Hugh Benson''' [[Institute of the Brothers of the Christian Schools|AFSC]] [[Order of St. Gregory the Great|KC*SG]] [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre|KGCHS]] (18 November 1871 &ndash; 19 October 1914) was an English [[Church of England|Anglican]] priest who in 1903 was received into the [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic Church]] in which he was ordained [[Catholic priest|priest]] in 1904. He was a prolific writer of fiction and wrote the notable dystopian novel ''[[Lord of the World]]'' (1907). His output encompassed historical, horror and science fiction, contemporary fiction, children's stories, plays, [[apologetics]], devotional works and articles. He continued his writing career at the same time as he progressed through the hierarchy to become a Chamberlain to [[Pope Pius X]] in 1911 and gain the title of [[Monsignor]].\n\n== Early life ==\nBenson was the youngest son of [[Edward White Benson]] ([[Archbishop of Canterbury]]) and his wife, [[Mary Sidgwick Benson|Mary]], and the younger brother of [[Edward Frederic Benson]] and [[A. C. Benson|Arthur Christopher Benson]].<ref name=\"ma\">\n{{cite news|author=[[Mike Ashley (writer)|Ashley, Mike]]|title=The Essential Writers: Blood Brothers (Profile of E.F., A.C. and R. H. Benson)|work=[[Twilight Zone literature|Rod Serling's The Twilight Zone Magazine]]|pages= 63\u201370|date= May\u2013June 1984}}</ref>\n\nBenson was educated at [[Eton College]] and then studied classics and [[Anglican theology|theology]] at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]], from 1890 to 1893.<ref>{{acad|id=BN890RH|name=Benson, Robert Hugh}}</ref>\n\nIn 1895, Benson was ordained a priest in the [[Church of England]] by his father, who was the then Archbishop of Canterbury.\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Robert Hugh Benson in 1907.jpg|thumb|left|Robert Hugh Benson in 1907]]\nAfter his father died suddenly in 1896, Benson was sent on a trip to the [[Middle East]] to recover his own health. While there he began to question the status of the Church of England and to consider the claims of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. His own piety began to tend toward the [[High Church]] tradition, and he started exploring [[Anglican religious order|religious life in various Anglican communities]], eventually obtaining permission to join the [[Community of the Resurrection]].\n\nBenson made his profession as a member of the community in 1901, at which time he had no thoughts of leaving the Church of England. As he continued his studies and began writing, however, he became more and more uneasy with his own [[Anglican doctrine|doctrinal position]] and, on 11 September 1903, he was received into the [[Catholic Church]]. Benson was [[Catholic ordination|ordained]] as a Roman Catholic priest in 1904. As the son of the late Archbishop of Canterbury, his conversion and his subsequent ordination, caused a sensation.<ref>Pearce, Joseph.[http://www.catholicauthors.com/benson.html \"R.H. Benson: Unsung Genius\", ''Lay Witness'']</ref>  \n\nHis first assignment was as a college chaplain. Although possessed of a \"reedy, stuttering voice\", Benson was a popular preacher, attracting large audiences wherever he spoke. In 1914, he visited the [[University of Notre Dame]] and gave an address on the papacy. Both ''Confessions of a Convert'' (1913) and ''Lourdes'' (1914) were serialized in Notre Dame's ''Ave Maria'' magazine, before appearing as books. <ref>[http://archives.nd.edu/episodes/visitors/rhb/ \"Robert Hugh Benson\", University of Notre Dame archives]</ref>\n\nHe was awarded the Dignitary of Honour of the [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre]].\n\n===Novelist===\nBenson continued his writing career along with his ministry as a priest. Like both his brothers, [[Edward Frederic Benson]] (\"Fred\") and [[A. C. Benson|Arthur Christopher Benson]], Robert wrote many [[Ghost story|ghost]] and [[horror fiction|horror]] stories, as well as children's stories and historical fiction. His horror and ghost fiction are collected in ''The Light Invisible'' (1903) and ''A Mirror of Shallott'' (1907).<ref name=\"ma\" /> His novel, ''[[Lord of the World]]'' (1907), is generally regarded as one of the first modern [[dystopian]] novels.<ref name=\"ma\" /> In the future he predicted there, the [[Anglican Church]] and other Protestant denominations would crumble and disappear in face of a rising tide of Secularism and Atheism, leaving the Catholic Church as the sole upholder and defender of Christianity - which helps explain his own personal choice. In the future he predicted in 1911 in ''The Dawn of All'', the Catholic Church fares better than in the previous book and emerges victorious in England and worldwide by the end of the 20th Century; this book is also notable in its fairly accurate prediction of a global network of a passenger air travel <ref>Maxim Shadurski, \"Religion and Science in Robert Hugh Benson's The Dawn of All\", article\u2002in\u2002\"English Studies\" 94(4), June 2013\u2002- see online abstract \n[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/263254362_Religion_and_Science_in_Robert_Hugh_Benson's_The_Dawn_of_All_1911]</ref>.  ''Come Rack! Come Rope!'' (1912) is a historical novel describing the [[Anti-Catholicism in the United Kingdom|persecution of English Roman Catholics]] during the Elizabethan era. <ref>Richard Griffiths, ''Pen and the Cross: Catholicism and English Literature 1850 - 2000''. London: A&C Black, 2010 {{ISBN|9780826496973}} (pp. 83-5).</ref> The bibliography below reveals a prodigious output.\n\nAmong his historical novels is the Reformation Trilogy: ''By What Authority'' (1905), ''The King\u2019s Achievement'' (1905), and ''The Queen\u2019s Tragedy'' (1907).<ref>[https://www.catholicworldreport.com/2015/07/10/the-fiction-of-robert-hugh-benson/ Applegarth, Anne. \"The Fiction of Robert Hugh Benson\", ''The Catholic World Report'', July 10, 2015]</ref>\n\n===Vatican chaplaincy===\nBenson was appointed a [[Chaplain of His Holiness|supernumerary private chamberlain]] to the Pope ([[Pius X]]) in 1911 and consequently styled as [[Monsignor]].{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n==Private life==\nAs a young man, Benson recalled, he had rejected the idea of marriage as \"quite inconceivable\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Benson, Robert Hugh|title=Confessions of a Convert|url=https://archive.org/details/ConfessionsOfAConvert1913|publisher= Longmans, Green and Co.|year= 1913}}</ref> He had a close friendship with \"Baron Corvo\", ''alias'' the novelist [[Frederick Rolfe]], with whom he had hoped to write a book on [[Thomas Becket|St Thomas Becket]], until Benson decided that he should not be associated (according to writer Brian Masters)<ref name=Telegraph>{{cite news |first=Christopher |last=Howse |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3637045/Sacred-mysteries.html |title=Sacred mysteries |type=opinion |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=3 February 2007 }}</ref> \"with a Venetian pimp and procurer of boys\". Nevertheless he maintained his friendship with [[Lord Alfred Douglas]], the friend and lover of [[Oscar Wilde]], and when an acquaintance protested that the connection with Douglas was inappropriate for him, he replied: \"Lord Alfred Douglas is my friend, and he'll come down when he likes!\"<ref name=Telegraph>{{cite news |first=Christopher |last=Howse |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3637045/Sacred-mysteries.html |title=Sacred mysteries |type=opinion |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=3 February 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nBenson died of pneumonia in 1914 in Salford, where he had been preaching a mission. He was 42. At his request, he was buried in the orchard of [[Hare Street House]], his house in the Hertfordshire village of Hare Street.<ref>{{cite book |last= Benson |first=A.C. |date= |title= Hugh: Memoirs of a Brother |url= http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/18615 |location= |publisher=Dodo Press |page=210 |isbn=1406548197 |accessdate= }}</ref> A chapel, dedicated to St Hugh, was built over the site. Benson bequeathed the house to the Catholic Church as a county retreat for the [[Archbishop of Westminster]]. The Roman Catholic church in the nearby town of [[Buntingford]], which he helped finance, is dedicated to St Richard of Chichester, but also known as the [[Benson Memorial Church]].<ref>[https://taking-stock.org.uk/?s=Benson+Memorial+Church \"Buntingford \u2013 St Richard of Chichester\", Taking Stock, Catholic Bishops' Conference of England and Wales]</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the house was put up for sale.  Benson's body was exhumed, and moved to the crypt of St. Edmund's College in Old Hall Green.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/Saveharestreethouse/photos/a.231260830836600/428875191075162/?type=3&theater</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Color Portrair of Robert Hugh Benson.jpg|Portrait of Benson\n\nFile:The Master's Lodge, Wellington College, 1868.jpg|Benson's birthplace. From the book ''Hugh, Memoirs of a Brother''\n\nFile:Robert Hugh Benson and Beth at the Chancery, Lincoln, in 1876, aged 5.jpg|Benson, aged 5, with Beth at the Chancery, Lincoln, in 1876. From the book ''Hugh, Memoirs of a Brother''\n\nFile:A. C. Benson, R. H. Benson, and E. F. Benson, 1882.jpg|[[A. C. Benson]], R. H. Benson and [[E. F. Benson]], 1882. From the book ''Hugh, Memoirs of a Brother''\n\nFile:Robert Hugh Benson in 1889, aged 17. As Steerer in the St. George, at Eton.jpg|Benson in 1889, aged 17, as Steerer in the St George at Eton. From the book ''Hugh, Memoirs of a Brother''\n</gallery>\n\n==Works==\n\n'''Science fiction'''\n* [https://archive.org/stream/amirrorshalottb00bensgoog#page/n8/mode/2up ''A Mirror of Shalott,''] Benziger Brothers, 1907.\n* [https://archive.org/stream/lordofworld00bens#page/n5/mode/2up ''Lord of the World,''] Dodd, Mead & Company, 1908 [1st Pub. 1907].\n* [https://archive.org/stream/dawnofall00bensiala#page/n1/mode/2up ''The Dawn of All,''] B. Herder, 1911.<ref>[http://www